  "prompt": "What could be the speed of light squared, as per Albert Einstein's theory?",
  "response": "In Albert Einstein's theory of relativity, the speed of light squared (\\(c^2\\)) is a fundamental constant that relates energy (\\(E\\)) to mass (\\(m\\)) in the famous equation:\n\n\\[\nE = mc^2\n\\]\n\nThe speed of light in a vacuum (\\(c\\)) is approximately **299,792,458 meters per second (m/s)**. Therefore, the speed of light squared is:\n\n\\[\nc^2 = (299,792,458 \\, \\text{m/s})^2 \\approx 8.9875 \\times 10^{16} \\, \\text{m}^2/\\text{s}^2\n\\]\n\nThis value is crucial in physics, as it demonstrates the equivalence of energy and mass, a cornerstone of Einstein's theory of relativity.",
